		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Traffic Message Channel</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Traffic Message Channel (TMC)</b> is a technology for delivering traffic and travel information to drivers. It is typically digitally coded using the <a href="/wiki/Radio_Data_System" title="Radio Data System">FM-RDS</a> system on conventional <a href="/wiki/FM_radio" title="FM radio" class="mw-redirect">FM radio</a> <a href="/wiki/Broadcasting" title="Broadcasting">broadcasts</a>. It can also be transmitted on <a href="/wiki/Digital_Audio_Broadcasting" title="Digital Audio Broadcasting">DAB</a> or <a href="/wiki/Satellite_radio" title="Satellite radio">satellite radio</a>. It allows silent delivery of high quality accurate, timely and relevant information, in the language chosen by the user and without interrupting normal services. Services, both public and commercial, are now operational in many European countries. When data is integrated directly into a <a href="/wiki/In-car_navigation" title="In-car navigation" class="mw-redirect">navigation system</a>, this gives the driver the option to take alternative routes to avoid traffic incidents.</p>
